
<blockquote class="wp-block-quote is-layout-flow wp-block-quote-is-layout-flow">
<p>French economist Serge Latouche, writing in <em>Le monde Diplomatique</em>, says the purpose of degrowth is “not a concrete project but a keyword,” which challenges the “tyranny [that] has made imaginative thinking outside the box impossible.</p>



<p>“What really matters is that we reject continuing destruction in the name of development,” he added.</p>



<p>At its core, degrowth proposes a decline in wasteful energy and material consumption habits, with decisions about resource allocation made via local participatory democracy instead of the whims of a global capitalist class. It’s about replacing an economics of “desire” with one of “need,” in which ecological and social values are placed at the forefront of allocating resources.</p>
</blockquote>



